    "company": "Middesk",
    "compensation": "",
    "content_hash": "8738f7699d1633b1",
    "department": "Marketing",
    "description": "About Middesk\n\nMiddesk makes it easier for businesses to work together. Since 2018, we’ve been transforming business identity verification, replacing slow, manual processes with seamless access to complete, up-to-date data. Our platform helps companies across industries confidently verify business identities, onboard customers faster, and reduce risk at every stage of the customer lifecycle.\n\nMiddesk came out of Y Combinator, is backed by Sequoia Capital and Accel Partners, and was recently named to Forbes Fintech 50 List.\n\n\nABOUT THE ROLE:\n\nYou'll own Middesk's data-driven storytelling for national media. This role turns real-time news cycles, government and fraud trends, and Middesk data into timely, credible insights that earn coverage in top-tier outlets.\n\nThis is not a content marketing role or a PR generalist role. It's an investigative research and analytical storytelling role for someone who can read the news, spot where data adds clarity, conduct original research, and work closely with a data scientist to produce insights journalists actually want.\n\nYour output is clear: original data stories backed by rigorous research that land in national media and build Middesk's credibility in high-visibility conversations.\n\n\nWHAT YOU'LL DO:\n\n - Original research \u0026 investigations: Lead deep, proactive research that uncovers novel insights, including:\n   \n   - Filing and tracking Freedom of Information requests to surface public data others aren't using\n   \n   - Researching and synthesizing academic studies, regulatory filings, and government reports\n   \n   - Interviewing subject-matter experts, academics, regulators, and industry practitioners to build context and credibility\n   \n   - Identifying emerging patterns in fraud, business formation, and enforcement before they hit the news cycle\n   \n   - Building ongoing relationships with researchers and experts who can validate or challenge findings\n\n - Data-driven media storytelling: Own Middesk's external, data-led media narratives, including:\n   \n   - News-cycle-driven data insights\n   \n   - Original data analyses tied to fraud, business identity, and government trends\n   \n   - Media-ready narratives, charts (in collaboration with our brand designer), and story angles\n   \n   - Translate complex data into clear, defensible insights that journalists can quickly understand and trust\n\n - News cycle \u0026 trend intelligence: Proactively identify moments where Middesk data can add signal, context, or counterpoint to the public conversation. Be the first at the company to spot and react to:\n   \n   - Fraud trends\n   \n   - Government enforcement actions\n   \n   - Regulatory changes\n   \n   - High-profile cases and policy moments\n   \n   - Broader business and economic news tied to entities and identity\n\n - Partnership with data science: Work in tight partnership with a dedicated data scientist to:\n   \n   - Shape hypotheses based on news, research findings, and emerging trends\n   \n   - Define analyses that are fast, relevant, and defensible\n   \n   - Pressure-test findings before they go external\n   \n   - Turn raw outputs into clear storylines, headlines, and talking points\n\n - Media narrative packaging \u0026 pitching: Develop complete, media-ready story packages, including:\n   \n   - Clear story angles and headlines\n   \n   - Key findings and takeaways\n   \n   - Supporting charts or data points\n   \n   - Quotable context journalists can reference\n\n - Credibility \u0026 quality bar: Act as the final editorial checkpoint for all external data stories, ensuring Middesk earns trust through rigor and evidence. Do this by:\n   \n   - Maintaining a high bar for accuracy, defensibility, clear sourcing and methodology, and non-promotional, insight-first framing\n   \n   - Ensuring Middesk's data stories can withstand journalist skepticism, public scrutiny, and regulatory or policy-aware audiences\n\n\nHOW SUCCESS IS MEASURED:\n\n - Media impact\n   \n   - Consistent placement of Middesk data stories in national and top-tier outlets\n   \n   - Journalists proactively referencing or returning to Middesk for data-backed context\n\n - Research quality \u0026 depth\n   \n   - Original insights that couldn't exist without your investigative work\n   \n   - Freedom of information requests, expert interviews, and academic research directly inform published stories\n\n - Timeliness \u0026 relevance\n   \n   - Middesk data is tied to active news cycles, not retrospective thought pieces\n   \n   - Stories feel timely, necessary, and additive to the conversation\n\n - Data credibility\n   \n   - Insights are quoted accurately and not walked back\n   \n   - Middesk is seen as a reliable and serious source, not a hype-driven commentator\n\n - Internal leverage\n   \n   - Middesk leadership relies on your work to respond quickly to breaking news\n   \n   - Data stories reduce the need for reactive scrambling by creating a repeatable motion\n\n\n\n\n\nWE'RE LOOKING FOR SOMEONE WITH:\n\n - 8+ years in data storytelling, investigative journalism, investigative reporting, research, or insight-driven content roles\n\n - Proven experience conducting original research including filing FOI/FOIA requests, analyzing public records, and synthesizing academic or regulatory sources\n\n - Experienced interviewing academics, experts, regulators, customers, and subject-matter experts to build depth and credibility\n\n - Proven experience turning research and data into stories that land in national or top-tier media\n\n - Strong instinct for news value: you know what's interesting now\n\n - Comfortable working closely with data scientists and questioning assumptions\n\n - Clear, disciplined writer who can explain complex findings without oversimplifying\n\n - Calm under pressure and comfortable working on tight timelines\n\n - Calmly opinionated: you can defend narrative choices without being rigid\n\n - Motivated by clarity, credibility, and long-term impact, not content volume or trends",
